         <abstract>
            <p>When no transactions in claims on a business venture are possible between the beginning and end of the venture, interim accounting reports have no economic function whatever. On the other hand, when such transactions are possible, information bearing on the venture's future cash flows is the only information investors require to establish interim prices for these claims. A new way of thinking about accounting developed by the authors, called Estimation Theory, explains how traditional accounting numbers can convey useful information about the expected magnitude of the future cash flows.</p>
          </abstract>
